## 10. Refactoring Rules

### 10.1 When to Refactor

Refactor when:

- Duplicate subsystems cause bugs (dual AgentManager, dual agent execution)
- File exceeds maintainability threshold (~300 lines of mixed concerns)
- Circular imports appear
- Test coverage cannot be added due to structure
- Dead code misleads contributors

Do **not** refactor unrelated code during feature work.

### 10.2 Refactoring Process

1. Read affected modules and callers (see Section 22)
2. Write or update tests first when behavior must be preserved
3. Make smallest refactor achieving goal
4. Verify `python main.py` still starts
5. Verify no new circular imports
6. Update this rulebook section if architectural rule changed

### 10.3 Behavior-Preserving Refactors

Default assumption: refactors preserve external behavior unless explicitly changing product behavior.

Document intentional behavior changes.

### 10.4 Deleting Code

Before deletion:

- Grep for imports and references
- Confirm no runtime path uses module
- Remove from composition root if wired

Prefer delete over `# commented out old code`.

### 10.5 Consolidation Priority List

High-priority consolidations (do when touching related code):

1. Single `AgentManager` instance shared by `Titan` and `Brain`
2. Remove duplicate agent execution in `Titan.start()` and `Brain.think()` — one orchestration path only
3. Unified memory facade
4. Retire `core/context.py` or merge into `context/context_manager.py`
5. Wire `brain/identity.py` and constitution summary into LLM instructions
6. Wire or delete `core/action_manager.py`

### 10.6 Migration of JSON Schemas

When changing `data/*.json` structure:

- Implement `default_schema()` fallback
- Optionally migrate on load with version field
- Never corrupt existing user data silently

