## 20. Security

### 20.1 Secrets

- `.env` in `.gitignore` always
- Never commit API keys, tokens, passwords
- Never print secrets to console or logs
- Cursor agents must warn if user attempts to commit `.env`

### 20.2 Data Privacy

- `data/long_term_memory.json` contains personal user information — treat as sensitive
- Do not exfiltrate memory contents to external services beyond configured LLM provider
- LLM prompts: minimize personal data to what is necessary for the task

### 20.3 Tool Execution (Future)

When adding code execution or file tools:

- Sandboxed execution
- Path allowlist within project directory
- No arbitrary shell from LLM without confirmation mode
- Trading tools require explicit risk limits and paper trading default

### 20.4 Input Sanitization

- Do not use `eval()` on user or LLM input
- Do not construct SQL/shell commands via string concat without parameterization
- Validate file paths prevent directory traversal (`../` attacks)

### 20.5 Dependency Security

- Review new dependencies for maintenance and reputation
- Pin versions in production deployments

### 20.6 Multi-User Authority

Nolan and Ibrahim have equal authority in product terms. Code must not embed backdoors or hidden preference for one user in agent logic.

